                    nutritional status? (ii) Does the presence of\n                    \n                      N\n                    \n                    in nectar affect the capacity of bats to discriminate and select other nectar traits such as sugar concentration? and (iii) Are bats able to distinguish among the flavours generated by the amino acid relative abundance present in the nectar from plants they typically encounter in nature?\n                  \n                \n                \n                  \n                    Our results showed that: (i) bats did not consider nectar N content regardless of their\n                    \n                      N\n                    \n                    nutritional condition, (ii) the nectar specialist\n                    \n                      L\n                      .\u00a0yerbabuenae\n                    \n                    showed a preference for the most concentrated sugar\u2010only nectar but changed to be indifferent when nectar contained\n                    \n                      N\n                    \n                    , and (iii)\n                    \n                      L\n                      .\u00a0yerbabuenae\n                    \n                    preferred diets without amino acids and preferred the taste of the amino acids present in the nectar of\n                    \n                      P\n                      achycereus pecten\n                    \n                    (Cactaceae) over those present in the nectar of\n                    \n                      C\n                      eiba aesculifolia\n                    \n                    (Bombacaceae).\n                  \n                \n                \n                  \n                    Our results suggest that regardless of the low concentrations at which\n                    \n                      N\n                    \n                    and amino acids are present in floral nectar, their presence affects bats' food selection by interfering with the bats' ability to detect differences in sugar concentrations, and by offering particular flavours that can be perceived and selected by nectarivorous bats. We discuss the ecological implications of the presence of\n                    \n                      N\n                    \n                    and amino acids in nectar on bats' foraging decisions.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Rodr\u00edguez\u2010Pe\u00f1a, Nelly", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Stoner, Kathryn E.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Ayala\u2010Berdon, Jorge", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Flores\u2010Ortiz, Cesar M.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Duran, Angel", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Schondube, Jorge E.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Cotter, Sheena", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/b814534e75c7a159609578bf630f8f18", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/33f6072acc0d44460118eb4a7de5cc3b089d404b58aee38a56464775c3e6826e", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/NNV2HT5B", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/NNV2HT5B", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/0aec9de28c2c7007397fd829a2e478ea!/b260285-262784", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "pub